text: 46,XX gonadal dysgenesis is a condition where a person with 46 chromosomes (XY) has underdeveloped or non-functional ovaries, which can cause problems in sexual development and puberty. The term "gonadal dysgenesis" refers specifically to this type of underdevelopment or absence of functional gonads, while "ovarian dysgenesis" refers to the same condition but with a focus on the ovaries.

That is correct. Hyperkalemic periodic paralysis (HPP) is a type of familial periodic paralysis, and it is characterized by episodes of muscle weakness and paralysis due to high levels of potassium in the body. Familial hyperkalemic periodic paralysis (FHKPP) specifically refers to this condition when passed down through families. It's important to note that while HPP can be inherited, not everyone with the gene will develop the condition. Additionally, other factors such as diet and medications can also affect potassium levels in the body and contribute to symptoms.

text: Hypokalemic periodic paralysis is a condition in which there is recurrent episodes of muscle weakness and paralysis, often associated with low potassium levels (hypokalemia) in the blood. It is considered to be a type of familial periodic paralysis.

Farmers lung, also known as extrinsic allergic alveolitis, is a type of respiratory condition caused by the inhalation of spores from moldy hay or straw. It typically presents with symptoms such as cough, fever, and breathlessness, and is characterized by inflammation of the alveoli (small air sacs) in the lungs.

brucella melitensis brucellosis is a specific type of brucellosis that is caused by the bacterium Brucella melitensis and can affect cattle, goats, sheep, and humans. It is characterized by symptoms such as fever, malaise, anorexia, limb pain, and back pain.

brucella abortus brucellosis is a type of disease that affects cattle and humans.
brucella abortus brucellosis is a type of something that has symptoms such as fever, chills, sweats, weight loss, malaise, headaches, myalgia, and arthralgia.
brucella abortus brucellosis has a specific definition as an infection caused by Brucella abortus [NCBITaxon:235] that results in the disease.

Hemangioma of the orbit, also known as Angioma of the orbit, is a type of orbital disease that occurs when there is an abnormal growth of blood vessels in the region surrounding the eyes. It is believed to be derived from endothelial cells and can cause various symptoms such as protrusion of the eyeball (proptosis), double vision (diplopia), or visual impairment. Treatment options may include surgery, radiation therapy, or embolization to help alleviate these symptoms and prevent further growth of blood vessels in the affected area.

Cavernous hemangioma of the orbit, also known as cavernous angioma of the orbit, is a type of vascular lesion that occurs in the eye. It is characterized by the presence of dilated blood vessels or cavernous spaces within the tissue of the orbit. These lesions can be congenital or acquired and may cause symptoms such as redness, pain, and vision loss if they are located near the optic nerve or other critical structures in the eye. It is important to consult an ophthalmologist for proper diagnosis and treatment if you suspect that you have a cavernous hemangioma of the orbit.

Neuroleptic Malignant Syndrome (NMS) is a rare but serious condition that can occur when someone takes certain medications, particularly antipsychotics. It affects the nervous system and can cause symptoms such as high fever, stiff muscles, altered consciousness, and changes in heart function.

Hantavirus pulmonary syndrome is a type of viral infectious disease that results in infection located in the lungs. It has a material basis in various strains of the Orthohantavirus family, which are transmitted by different rodent species like deer mice, cotton rats, marsh rice rats, small vesper mice, and rice rats. The infection is characterized by symptoms such as fever, muscle pain, headache, cough, vomiting, and chills, which rapidly progress to bilateral interstitial pulmonary infiltrates, pulmonary edema, and hypoxia often resulting in death from shock or cardiac complications.

Pemphigoid gestationis is a type of pemphigoid that occurs during pregnancy and is characterized by the development of erythematous papules, vesicles, and plaques around the trunk and extremities. It also has symptoms such as pruritis and is caused by autoantibodies to the basement membrane, which triggers a complement cascade and attracts eosinophils to the subepidermis. Another name for this condition is Gestational herpes.

text: chorea gravidarum is a type of choreatic disease.

Sporotrichosis is a type of fungal infection that occurs due to the growth of Sporothrix schenckii, a pathogenic yeast. It can cause various symptoms such as skin lesions and even spread to other parts of the body if not treated properly. The condition typically begins with small red or purple spots on the skin, which can progress to form larger, reddish-brown nodules or even ulcers. In some cases, it may also affect internal organs, leading to systemic infection and potentially life-threatening complications.

Ureteral lymphoma is a rare form of cancer that affects the ureters, which are tubes that carry urine from the kidneys to the bladder. It occurs when lymphocytes, a type of white blood cell, grow and multiply uncontrollably in the ureter. Symptoms may include pain or discomfort in the abdomen or back, blood in the urine, frequent or small amounts of urine, and swelling of the legs or feet. Treatment typically involves a combination of chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and surgery to remove the affected ureter.

Regional ureteric cancer refers to a type of malignant tumor that develops in the ureters, which are the tubes that transport urine from the kidneys to the bladder. It is also known as regional Ureteric carcinoma or regional malignant ureteral tumor.

Dumping syndrome is a condition that affects individuals who have undergone gastric bypass surgery. It occurs when food moves too quickly through the small intestine, causing symptoms such as nausea, abdominal pain, and diarrhea. The exact synonym for this condition is Jejunal syndrome.

Death usually occurs within the first year of life." ;
    :has_exact_match "OMIM:620151",
        "ORDO:75233" ;
    :has_exact_synonym "acute infantile lysosomal acid lipase deficiency",
        "complete LAL deficiency",
        "complete LIPA deficiency",
        "complete cholesterol ester hydrolase deficiency",
        "complete lysosomal acid lipase deficiency",
        "Acid esterase deficiency"@en,
        "Acid lipase deficiency"@en,
        "Wolman xanthomatosis"@en,
        "Wolman's disease"@en,
        "Wolman's or triglyceride storage type III disease"@en,
        "Xanthomatosis, familial"@en .
text: Wolman disease is a rare genetic disorder that affects the liver, spleen, and other organs. It is caused by a deficiency of lysosomal acid lipase, which leads to the accumulation of cholesteryl esters and triglycerides throughout the body. This can result in severe symptoms such as hepatosplenomegaly (enlarged liver and spleen), malnutrition, jaundice, vomiting, diarrhea, and steatorrhea (greasy stools). The disease is usually fatal within the first year of life without treatment. It is also known as acid esterase deficiency, acid lipase deficiency, Wolman xanthomatosis, Wolman's disease, or triglyceride storage type III disease.

Lipoid proteinosis is a type of lipid metabolism disorder characterized by the buildup of lipids and other fatty substances in body tissues. It can affect various organs, including the heart, lungs, kidneys, and pancreas. There are several types of lipoid proteinosis, each with specific symptoms and treatments.
Lipoid proteinosis is also known by its synonym Lipid proteinosis or URBACH-WIETHE DISEASE. This condition occurs when the body has trouble breaking down fats and cholesterol, leading to the accumulation of fatty substances in various tissues. It can be inherited or acquired through certain medical conditions, such as cystic fibrosis and hypothyroidism.
If left untreated, lipoid proteinosis can lead to serious complications, including organ damage and failure. Therefore, it is essential for those affected by this condition to work closely with their healthcare providers to develop an appropriate treatment plan that addresses their specific needs.

Fabry disease is a type of sphingolipidosis, which is characterized by the buildup of globotriaosylceramide in the body's cells due to X-linked inherited mutations in the GLA gene. It has exact synonyms like Alpha-galactosidase A deficiency, Angiokeratoma Corporis Diffusum, Fabry Disease, Cardiac Variant, Fabry's disease, and deficiency of melibiase.

Fucosidosis is a type of lysosomal storage disease characterized by the accumulation of fucose-containing molecules in various tissues and organs, primarily affecting the brain and spinal cord. It occurs due to a deficiency or absence of the enzyme alpha-fucosidase, which is responsible for breaking down fucose-containing oligosaccharides and preventing their accumulation in the lysosome. The deficiency can be inherited from both parents (recessive inheritance) or due to a new genetic mutation (de novo mutation).

Fucosidosis symptoms usually begin during infancy and childhood, with a gradual progression of neurological signs, muscle stiffness, and progressive motor skills loss. Common symptoms include mental retardation, seizures, ataxia, and microcephaly. In severe cases, it can lead to life-threatening complications such as respiratory failure and cardiomyopathy.

Diagnosis of fucosidosis typically involves a combination of clinical examination, laboratory tests (such as enzyme assays or DNA sequencing), and imaging studies (MRI, CT scan). Treatment for fucosidosis usually focuses on managing symptoms and improving quality of life. Enzyme replacement therapy with recombinant alpha-fucosidase may help in breaking down the accumulated fucose-containing oligosaccharides, while other supportive care measures like nutritional interventions, speech therapy, and physical therapy can improve functioning and quality of life.

In conclusion, fucosidosis is a lysosomal storage disease characterized by the accumulation of fucose-containing oligosaccharides in various tissues and organs, primarily affecting the brain and spinal cord. It occurs due to a deficiency or absence of the enzyme alpha-fucosidase, which can be inherited or caused by new genetic mutations. With early diagnosis and appropriate treatment, many affected individuals can lead relatively normal lives despite the progressive nature of their condition.

Sjogren-Larsson Syndrome (SLS) is a rare, autosomal recessive genetic disorder characterized by the following symptoms: ichthyosis, mental retardation, spastic paraparesis, macular dystrophy, and leukoencephalopathy. It is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ALDH3A2 gene on chromosome 17p11. SLS has exact synonyms such as FALDH deficiency, Sjogren syndrome, and fatty acid alcohol oxidoreductase deficiency.

Cholesterol ester storage disease (CESD) is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the accumulation of cholesteryl esters and triglycerides in the liver and spleen due to a deficiency in lysosomal acid lipase. It typically presents in childhood or later with symptoms such as recurrent abdominal pain, jaundice, fatigue, and itching. The condition can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and spleen, and may also affect other organs. CESD is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, meaning that a person must inherit two copies of the gene for the disorder to develop. Diagnosis is typically made through genetic testing and measurement of lysosomal acid lipase levels in the blood. Treatment options include dietary changes, enzyme replacement therapy, and liver transplantation in severe cases.

Neuronal ceroid lipofuscinosis is a type of lipid storage disease that affects the central nervous system and leads to progressive neurological decline. It is also known as hereditary ceroid lipofuscinosis, which refers specifically to the inherited form of this condition.

Niemann-Pick disease is a type of sphingolipidosis. Sphingolipidoses are a group of rare genetic metabolic disorders characterized by the accumulation of lipids, such as sphingomyelin, in various cellular components and tissues due to defects in the metabolism of these lipids. The name "Niemann-Pick" comes from the two doctors who first described the condition: Franz Xaver Niemann (1854-1916) and Rudolf Ludwig Pick (1870-1939).

There are different types of Niemann-Pick disease, which are classified based on the specific type of lipid that is accumulating in the body. The most common form is called Type C, which affects infants and children and is characterized by the buildup of sphingomyelin in the liver, spleen, brain, and other organs. Other types include Type A, which primarily affects the liver and spleen, and Type B, which affects the liver, spleen, and lymphatic system.

Niemann-Pick disease is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, meaning that a child must inherit two copies of the faulty gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition. There is currently no cure for Niemann-Pick disease, but treatments are available to help manage its symptoms and improve quality of life. These may include enzyme replacement therapy, substrate reduction therapy, and supportive care.

Peripheral degeneration of cornea is a type of corneal degeneration that affects the peripheral area of the cornea. It can lead to symptoms such as blurred vision, sensitivity to light, and difficulty seeing objects in the periphery. Peripheral degenerations of cornea refer to any condition that causes damage or deterioration of the peripheral parts of the cornea, which may affect its transparency and shape. Some common causes of peripheral degeneration of cornea include aging, trauma, infections, and autoimmune disorders. Treatment options depend on the underlying cause and severity of the condition but may include medications, surgery, or corrective lenses to improve vision.

Candidal Paronychia is a type of Candidiasis, which is a fungal infection caused by the overgrowth of Candida species. It primarily affects the outer layer of the nail and can cause painful, red, swollen areas around the nail, often at the cuticle or site of a hangnail or other injury. It is also known as Candidiasis of the skin and nails.

WAGR syndrome is a genetic disorder caused by the deletion of part of chromosome 11. It is characterized by the absence of the iris (Aniridia), Wilms tumor, genitourinary anomalies, and mental retardation. The condition results from the loss of several genes on the short arm of chromosome 11, which makes it one of the best-studied examples of a disorder caused by the deletion of neighboring (contiguous) genes. It is also known as 11p partial monosomy syndrome, Wilms tumor-Aniridia-Genitourinary Anomalies-Mental Retardation syndrome, and chromosome 11p13 deletion syndrome.

Retinal artery occlusion (RAO) refers to a blockage or obstruction of the blood vessels in the retina, which is the part of the eye responsible for processing visual information. There are two main types of RAO: central retinal artery occlusion and branch retinal vein occlusion.

Central retinal artery occlusion occurs when the main retinal artery is blocked, leading to a lack of blood flow to the retina. This can result in sudden vision loss and may cause permanent damage if not treated promptly. Symptoms usually develop within minutes to hours after the blockage occurs.

Branch retinal vein occlusion happens when a small blood vessel in the retina becomes blocked, leading to swelling of the retinal tissue. This can also result in sudden vision loss and may cause permanent damage if left untreated. Symptoms usually develop over several hours or days after the blockage occurs.

Treatment for RAO depends on the specific type and severity of the condition. In some cases, medical treatment may be sufficient to improve blood flow and reduce swelling in the retina. However, surgical intervention may also be necessary to remove the obstruction or bypass a blocked vessel. Early detection and prompt treatment are crucial for minimizing the risk of vision loss and other complications associated with RAO.

The Argyll-Robertson pupil is a type of abnormal pupillary function characterized by a small pupil, the absence of a pupillary light reflex and the retention of a normal pupillary near response. It is also sometimes referred to as the Argyll Robertson phenomenon or pupil, nonsyphilitic. This condition can be caused by certain infections or autoimmune disorders, and it is important for patients to seek medical attention if they experience any symptoms of this condition.

Senile degeneration of the brain is a type of neurodegenerative disease that affects the cerebral cortex and other regions of the brain. It is characterized by the progressive loss of neurons and synapses, leading to cognitive decline and memory loss. There are no specific treatments for this condition, but managing risk factors such as hypertension, diabetes, and smoking can help slow its progression.

Reye's syndrome is a type of syndrome.
Reye's syndrome has definition A condition characterized by acute brain damage and liver dysfunction, often resulting from the use of aspirin in children with viral illnesses. However, it can also occur without aspirin consumption..
Reye's syndrome has exact synonym Reye syndrome.

atrophic glossitis is a term used to describe a type of glossitis, which is an inflammation or thickening of the tongue. Specifically, atrophic glossitis refers to the thinning and atrophy of the papillae on the surface of the tongue. This condition can cause a smooth, shiny tongue, which may make it difficult to properly taste and handle food. It is important to note that while there are other terms used to describe similar conditions, such as "Hunter's glossitis" or "smooth atrophic tongue," they generally refer to the same condition of papillae loss on the tongue surface.

Malignant cardiac peripheral nerve sheath neoplasm, also known as MPNST of the heart, is a rare and aggressive type of cancer that affects the outer layer of nerves in the heart. It is considered a subtype of malignant peripheral nerve sheath tumors (MPNST) and is characterized by its high degree of malignancy and rapid growth rate. MPNST typically occurs in young adults and can cause symptoms such as chest pain, shortness of breath, and fainting due to the pressure it puts on the heart and surrounding structures. Treatment for MPNST of the heart usually involves a combination of surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation therapy, depending on the extent of the cancer and the patient's overall health.
The correct name for malignant cardiac germ cell tumor is "malignant germ cell tumor of the heart".
rete testis adenocarcinoma is a type of rete testis neoplasm that derives from epithelial cells of glandular origin.

Seminal vesicle adenocarcinoma is a type of male reproductive organ cancer. It is characterized by the presence of abnormal cells in the seminal vesicles, which are small glands located near the prostate gland. These glands produce sperm and seminal fluid. Seminal vesicle adenocarcinoma is relatively rare compared to other types of reproductive organ cancer, such as testicular or prostate cancer. It is usually treated with surgery and/or radiation therapy, depending on the stage of the cancer.

sphenoidal sinus cancer refers to a specific type of cancer that originates in the sphenoid sinus, which is a small air-filled cavity located near the base of the skull. Sphenoidal sinus cancer can also be referred to as malignant tumor of the sphenoid sinus or paranasal sinus cancer, depending on the location and extent of the cancer's spread. It is essential for patients with this condition to receive proper treatment, which may involve surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, or a combination of these approaches.

Sphenoid sinus squamous cell carcinoma is a type of cancer that originates from squamous epithelial cells and affects the sphenoidal sinus. It has a precise definition as a squamous cell carcinoma located in the sphenoid sinus, with an exact synonym being epidermoid carcinoma of the sphenoidal sinus.

Steroid-induced glaucoma, also known as steroid-responsive glaucoma, is a condition where the intraocular pressure in the eye increases due to the use of corticosteroids. This type of glaucoma is more common than primary open-angle glaucoma and angle-closure glaucoma combined. Steroid-induced glaucoma can develop rapidly, with symptoms appearing within a few weeks or even days after starting the steroid regimen. It is essential to monitor intraocular pressure closely when taking corticosteroids to prevent sudden increases in pressure that can cause vision loss if left untreated.

Geographic tongue, also known as benign migratory glossitis, is a condition characterized by a smooth, shiny, and sometimes reddish-pink surface on the top of the tongue. This condition can be caused by a variety of factors, including allergies, acid reflux, and autoimmune disorders. In some cases, geographic tongue may also be associated with other medical conditions, such as oral thrush or lichen planus. While it is not typically painful, geographic tongue can cause discomfort or annoyance due to its appearance. Treatment for this condition usually involves addressing any underlying causes and practicing good oral hygiene habits.

Primary pulmonary hypertension is a type of chronic pulmonary heart disease characterized by an increase in blood pressure within the lungs. It can cause symptoms such as shortness of breath, dizziness, fainting, and leg swelling. The exact cause of primary pulmonary hypertension is unknown, but it can be inherited or caused by certain medical conditions or medications. It is important to consult a doctor for proper diagnosis and treatment of this condition.

The term "disease of cellular proliferation" refers to a medical condition characterized by abnormal or excessive cell growth. This can include various types of cancer, as well as benign tumors and other conditions that involve uncontrolled cell division.

Neoplasm is another term used to describe this type of disease, which refers specifically to the abnormal growth of cells that have lost their normal functions and are capable of invading nearby tissues or spreading throughout the body. Cell process disease, on the other hand, may refer more broadly to any condition involving an imbalance in cellular processes, but it is not a specific term used to describe this particular class of diseases. Overall, these terms all generally refer to conditions that involve abnormal cell growth and can potentially be life-threatening if left untreated.

postsurgical hypothyroidism is a type of hypothyroidism.
postsurgical hypothyroidism has exact synonym Post-surgical hypothyroidism.
postsurgical hypothyroidism has exact synonym Postoperative hypothyroidism.

Hypothyroidism is a medical condition that occurs when the thyroid gland does not produce enough hormones. This can lead to a range of symptoms, including weight gain, fatigue, dry skin, and depression. It is important for those with hypothyroidism to work with their healthcare provider to manage their symptoms and ensure they are receiving proper treatment.

Atheroembolism of the kidney, also known as a renal artery stenosis, is a condition where the blood flow to the kidneys is restricted due to the narrowing or blockage of the renal arteries. This can lead to reduced blood supply and damage to the kidneys, potentially causing kidney disease. It is important to address this condition if it is diagnosed to prevent further damage and complications.

Cholesterol embolism is a type of vascular disease that occurs when cholesterol crystals break off from the inner lining of blood vessels and travel through the bloodstream, causing obstruction in smaller blood vessels. This can lead to symptoms such as pain, swelling, and discoloration (purple or blue) of the affected limb. It is also known by several other names, including atheroembolism, cholesterol crystal embolism, purple toe syndrome, trash foot, and warfarin blue toe syndrome.

Acrodysostosis is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the shortening of interphalangeal joints in the hands and/or feet, along with mental deficiency.

Serous labyrinthitis is a type of inner ear infection. It occurs when bacterial toxins enter the inner ear, causing inflammation and damage to the structures that help with balance and hearing. This condition can be caused by an acute or chronic middle ear infection. Acute serous labyrinthitis is another name for this type of labyrinthitis. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you have this condition, as it can cause severe symptoms such as vertigo, nausea, and hearing loss.

Hypertelorism microtia facial clefting syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by the combination of hypertelorism, cleft lip and palate, and microtia. It has an exact synonym in Bixler Christian Gorlin syndrome, Bixler syndrome, HMC syndrome, and Hypertelorism-microtia-facial clefting syndrome.

Multiple intestinal atresia (MIA) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the small and large intestines. It occurs when there are numerous atretic segments in the intestines due to mutations in the TTC7A gene on chromosome 2p21. The condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TTC7A gene. MIA can be diagnosed through imaging tests such as ultrasound, CT scan, and MRI. Treatment for MIA varies depending on the severity of the condition but may include surgery to remove non-functional segments of the intestine or dietary changes to manage symptoms. It is essential to consult with a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment options.

Vacterl association, also known as VATER syndrome, is a complex congenital disorder that affects multiple organ systems. It is characterized by the presence of at least three of the following defects: vertebral defects, anal atresia, cardiac defects, tracheo-esophageal fistula, renal anomalies, and limb abnormalities. The exact cause of VATER syndrome is not known, but it is thought to be a result of a combination of genetic and environmental factors. It can have serious health complications and requires careful monitoring and management by a team of specialists.

Labyrinthitis is a type of inner ear infection that affects the labyrinth, which is responsible for balance and hearing. It can cause symptoms such as dizziness, vertigo, and hearing loss. Labyrinthitis is also known as vestibular neuronitis.

Silver-Russell syndrome, also known as Silver Russell Dwarfism, is a rare genetic disorder that affects an individual's growth and development. It is characterized by severe intrauterine growth retardation, poor postnatal growth, craniofacial features such as a triangular-shaped face and a broad forehead, body asymmetry, and a variety of minor malformations. The exact cause of Silver-Russell syndrome is not yet fully understood, but it is believed to be related to abnormal chromosome number or structure. Treatment options for Silver-Russell syndrome may include medications to stimulate growth, nutritional interventions, and physical therapy.

Binder's syndrome, also known as maxillary and nasal dysplasia, is a congenital disorder characterized by abnormal development of the bones and soft tissues in the nose. It can cause various symptoms such as breathing problems, blockages, and facial asymmetry. Treatment typically involves surgery to correct the underlying structural issues and improve airflow through the nasal passages.

Axenfeld-Rieger syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the eye. It is characterized by abnormalities in the front part of the eye, specifically the anterior segment. These abnormalities can include issues with the cornea, iris, ciliary body, and other structures in the eye. The exact cause of Axenfeld-Rieger syndrome is not fully understood, but it is thought to be inherited as an autosomal dominant trait. This means that if one parent has the gene for the disorder, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit it. There is no cure for Axenfeld-Rieger syndrome, but treatments are available to manage the symptoms and improve vision.

Diastrophic dysplasia is a genetic disorder that affects the growth and development of bones, leading to short stature and characteristic skeletal abnormalities. It is caused by mutations in the SLC26A2 gene, which encodes for an enzyme involved in chondrocyte differentiation and bone matrix synthesis. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that to develop the disorder, an individual must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent).
Diastrophic dysplasia primarily affects the long bones of the extremities, leading to shortening and thickening of the bones. It also causes characteristic facial features such as a large forehead, prominent eyes, and a small jaw. The condition can lead to various complications, including spinal stenosis, scoliosis, and joint problems. However, with appropriate medical care, it can be managed to improve quality of life.

Smith-Lemli-Opitz syndrome (SLO) is a rare genetic disorder that affects lipid metabolism and can lead to various physical abnormalities, including craniosynostosis (premature fusion of skull bones), hypertelorism (wide-set eyes), low hairline, cleft lip/palate, clubfoot, and distinctive facial features such as a prominent jaw and large ears. The syndrome is caused by mutations in the DHCR7 gene, which encodes an enzyme involved in cholesterol biosynthesis. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that to develop the condition, an individual must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent). SLO can be diagnosed through a combination of clinical examination and genetic testing. There is no cure for the syndrome, but treatment may focus on managing symptoms and improving quality of life.

Clouston Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by abnormal hair, nails and skin. It affects sweat glands but not teeth. Clouston Syndrome is caused by a mutation in the GJB6 gene on chromosome 13q12. The condition has also been referred to as Hidrotic Ectodermal Dysplasia Syndrome, Ectodermal Dysplasia 2, Clouston Type, and Clouston's Hidrotic Ectodermal Dysplasia.

Johanson Blizzard Syndrome (JBS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple organ systems, including the pancreas, nose, scalp, and brain. It is characterized by abnormal development of these organs and tissues, which can lead to various physical and mental health problems.
JBS is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that a person needs to inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) in order to develop the disorder. This type of inheritance occurs when both parents pass on a defective copy of the gene, and there is a 25% chance that their child will have JBS if they are carriers.
Symptoms of JBS can vary widely depending on the severity of the abnormalities in each individual, but typically include growth failure, pancreatitis, hearing loss, and facial abnormalities such as cleft lip or palate. Mental retardation is also common, along with other developmental delays that can affect motor skills, speech, and social interactions.
There is no cure for JBS, but early intervention and appropriate medical care can help manage its symptoms and improve the quality of life for those affected by it. Genetic counseling and testing are also important for families with a history of JBS to understand their risk and make informed decisions about future pregnancies.

Galactokinase deficiency, also known as galactosemia type II, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to convert galactose, a simple sugar found in milk and other dairy products, into a usable form. The lack of galactokinase enzyme can lead to an accumulation of galactose and galactitol, which can cause damage to various tissues and organs in the body, particularly affecting the brain and liver. Symptoms typically appear within the first few days or weeks after birth and may include jaundice, lethargy, poor feeding, and vomiting. If left untreated, galactokinase deficiency can lead to severe health complications and even death. However, with proper medical care, including a diet low in galactose and regular monitoring of blood sugar levels, it is possible to manage the condition and prevent long-term damage.

Thrombocytopenia absent radius syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease that is characterized by the absence of the radius bone, thrombocytopenia (low platelet count), and bilateral absence of the radii with the presence of both thumbs. It has material basis in compound heterozygosity for a rare null mutation involving the RBM8A gene on chromosome 1q12 on one allele and 1 of 2 low-frequency noncoding single-nucleotide polymorphisms in RBM8A on the other. It has exact synonyms such as Radial aplasia-thrombocytopenia syndrome, Thrombocytopenia with absent radii (TAR) syndrome, and chromosome 1q21.1 deletion syndrome.

Major depressive disorder (MDD) is a mental health condition characterized by a persistent feeling of sadness or loss of interest and pleasure in daily activities, also known as anhedonia. It is accompanied by physical symptoms such as changes in appetite, sleep disturbances, low energy, and psychomotor agitation or retardation. Additionally, individuals with MDD may experience cognitive impairments, such as difficulty concentrating or making decisions, and feelings of worthlessness or guilt.

MDD can be triggered by various factors, including genetics, brain chemistry, life events, and medical conditions. Treatment typically involves a combination of medication and therapy to address the underlying causes and alleviate symptoms. In severe cases, hospitalization may be necessary for safety reasons. It is important to seek professional help if you suspect you or someone you know may be struggling with MDD.

Propionic acidemia is a type of organic acidemia that results from a nonfunctional propionyl-CoA carboxylase, which affects the conversion of amino acids and fats into sugar for energy. It can be diagnosed through blood tests that measure the levels of propionic acid and other related compounds. Treatment typically involves a special diet that is low in protein and high in carbohydrates to reduce the body's reliance on amino acids for energy, as well as medications to help with metabolism and prevent ketoacidosis.

Branchiootorenal syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects many organ systems in the body, including the ears, kidneys, and throat. It is caused by mutations in the FOXI1 gene, which regulates the development of various organs during embryonic growth.
Symptoms of branchiootorenal syndrome can vary widely among affected individuals, but typically include ear abnormalities (such as cysts or fistulas), hearing loss, kidney abnormalities, and throat abnormalities. Other features may also be present, such as skin tags and webbing between the fingers and toes.
Diagnosis of branchiootorenal syndrome is typically made through a combination of physical examination, imaging studies (such as X-rays or CT scans), and genetic testing. Treatment options may include surgery to address specific symptoms, such as correcting ear abnormalities or removing skin tags. Early intervention can help improve outcomes for affected individuals.
It is important to note that branchiootorenal syndrome is a rare disorder, and the prevalence is not well established. However, it is estimated to affect approximately 1 in 50,000 to 200,000 newborns worldwide.

Pfeiffer syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which means that it can be passed down through families. It is characterized by premature fusion in the skull bones and is caused by mutations in the FGFR1 and FGFR2 genes. This condition is also known as acrocephalosyndactylia type V.

FG syndrome is a type of X-linked recessive disease, which means that it is passed down through the mother's side of the family and can affect males more severely than females. It is characterized by several physical traits, including retardation, hyperactivity, hypotonia (low muscle tone), broad thumbs, big first toes, and a unique facial appearance with macrocephaly (large head size). It has an X-linked recessive inheritance pattern, which means that the gene for the condition is located on the X chromosome and requires two copies of the gene (one from each parent) for the disease to develop. Another name for FG syndrome is Keller syndrome, and it can also be referred to as Opitz-Kaveggia syndrome in some medical circles.

Centronuclear myopathy, also known as myotubular myopathy, is a type of congenital structural myopathy characterized by abnormally located nuclei in skeletal muscle cells. The nuclei are located in the center of the cell, instead of their normal location at the periphery. This condition can cause weakness and muscular fatigue, and may also affect the size and shape of muscles. It is important to note that while there may be some overlap between different types of myopathies, each one has its own unique set of characteristics and causes.

Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome (EDS) is a genetic disorder that affects the body's connective tissue, which provides support and structure to various organs and tissues. EDS Classic Type 1, also known as T1, is one of the subtypes of EDS, characterized by loose joints, skin that is easily bruised and fragile, and scars that heal in a distinctive "cigarette paper" pattern. It is caused by mutations in the COL5A1 gene on chromosome 9q34.

beta ketothiolase deficiency is a metabolic disorder that occurs due to the inability to process isoleucine and ketones. It primarily affects infants and is characterized by recurrent ketoacidotic attacks, which are marked by symptoms like vomiting, lethargy, dehydration, and seizures. The disorder has a genetic basis, specifically a mutation in the ACAT1 gene on chromosome 11q22.3, which causes the production of the ACAT1 enzyme to be reduced or absent.

This condition is also known as 2-methyl-3-hydroxybutyricacidemia, 3-ketothiolase deficiency, and Mitochondrial acetoacetyl-CoA Thiolase deficiency. It can be diagnosed through laboratory testing of blood samples for the presence of ketoacidosis and genetic testing to identify the specific gene mutation responsible for the disorder. Treatment typically involves the administration of insulin and other supportive measures to manage symptoms, such as dehydration and seizures.

Autosomal dominant microcephaly is a type of microcephaly that occurs due to mutations in certain autosomal genes. It is characterized by abnormal small head size, and can be passed down through families.

Weaver syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by prenatal and postnatal overgrowth, accelerated osseous maturation, characteristic craniofacial appearance, and developmental delay. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the EZH2 gene on chromosome 7q36. It is also known as Weaver-Williams syndrome or WEAVER-LIKE SYNDROME.

Hereditary angioedema (HAE) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that causes recurrent episodes of severe swelling of the skin and mucous membranes. It is characterized by the presence of C1 inhibitor, which is responsible for regulating the immune system's response to allergens and foreign substances. HAE can be triggered by various factors such as stress, illness, medication, or even physical trauma. Treatment options include medications that prevent or treat swelling, and in severe cases, plasma exchange or intravenous immunoglobulin may be necessary. It is essential for people with HAE to work closely with their healthcare providers to develop a treatment plan tailored to their individual needs.

Craniofrontonasal syndrome (CFNS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of the face and skull. It is caused by mutations in the EFNB1 gene, which is located on the X chromosome. The condition is more severe in females than in males due to the presence of two X chromosomes.
CFNS is characterized by hypertelorism (enlarged spaces between the eyes), frontonasal dysplasia (abnormal development of the forehead and nose), craniosynostosis (premature fusion of skull bones), bifid nasal tip, grooved nails, wiry hair, and abnormalities of the thoracic skeleton.
It is important to note that CFNS is a type of X-linked dominant inheritance, which means that it is passed down through the maternal line. Males with one copy of the mutated gene (hemizygous) typically have milder symptoms, while females require two copies to develop the full spectrum of the disorder (homozygous).

Aggressive periodontitis is a form of periodontal disease that affects individuals under the age of 16. It results in rapid attachment loss and bone destruction, often due to factors like dental plaque and tartar buildup, causing inflammation and damage to the periodontium. The condition has also been referred to as juvenile periodontitis.

To learn more about aggressive periodontitis or other dental topics, feel free to visit <https://www.medicinedefinitions.com>

trichorhinophalangeal syndrome type i is a type of autosomal dominant disease that has the definition as A syndrome characterized by short stature, sparse hair, a bulbous nasal tip and cone-shaped epiphyses (the growing ends of bones), as well as severe generalized shortening of all finger and toe bones (brachydactyly). It is also related to trichorhinophalangeal dysplasia type i.

Partington syndrome is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. This means that it is passed down through the X chromosome and can cause cognitive impairments, muscle weakness, and speech difficulties. Partington syndrome is also known as Russell-Silver syndrome when viewed from the perspective of genetic inheritance. It's important to note that this condition has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance.

Sotos syndrome, also known as cerebral gigantism, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by excessive growth during the first two to three years of life. It is caused by mutations in the fibroblast growth factor 3 (FGF3) gene, which is located on the long arm of chromosome 2. Sotos syndrome affects approximately one in every 10,000 live births and is more common in boys than girls.

Symptoms of Sotos syndrome include:

* Excessive growth during infancy and toddlerhood
* Average or above-average intelligence
* Tall stature
* Proportional skeletal growth, meaning that bones continue to grow at a normal rate after the growth spurt is over.
* Large hands and feet
* High muscle tone (hypertonia)
* Deep speech and slow speech patterns
* Mild to moderate behavioral problems
* Abnormal bone development can lead to an increased risk of fractures later in life.

Diagnosis is typically made through a combination of clinical examination, genetic testing, and imaging studies such as X-rays and MRI scans. Treatment for Sotos syndrome generally focuses on managing any associated health problems and ensuring that the child reaches their full growth potential.

In summary, Sotos syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by excessive growth during infancy and toddlerhood, along with other physical and developmental symptoms. It is important for individuals with Sotos syndrome to receive proper medical care and follow-up to monitor their growth and overall health.
Methylmalonic acidemia is a type of organic acidemia, which is characterized by an accumulation of methylmalonic acid in the blood. It is also known as methylmalonic aciduria.

Lymphangioma is a type of benign vascular tumor that occurs when the lymphatic vessels become dilated. It can occur in various parts of the body, including the head and neck, trunk, limbs, and genitals. Lymphangioma typically presents as a non-cancerous, slow-growing mass, and is often asymptomatic unless it becomes large or causes pressure symptoms. It can be treated with surgery or sclerotherapy, which involves injecting a solution into the tumor to cause it to shrink and eventually disappear.

Isovaleric acidemia is an organic acidemia that occurs due to the deficiency of isovaleryl-CoA dehydrogenase. This enzyme is responsible for breaking down isovaleric acid, which is one of the branched-chain amino acids. When this enzyme is deficient or not functioning properly, it can lead to an accumulation of isovaleric acid in the body, causing a variety of symptoms such as vomiting, abdominal pain, lethargy, and even coma. Isovaleric acidemia is usually inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person needs to inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition. Treatment typically involves dietary restrictions, such as avoiding or limiting the consumption of protein-rich foods, and medical management of symptoms as they arise.

Argininosuccinic aciduria is a type of amino acid metabolic disorder, where the body has difficulty breaking down argininosuccinate, which can lead to the accumulation of argininosuccinic acid in the blood and urine. It's also known as Argininosuccinate lyase deficiency, argininosuccinic acidemia, arginosuccinase deficiency, or deficiency of argininosuccinate lyase.

vascular type ehlers danlos syndrome is a form of the ehlers-danlos syndrome. it has a genetic basis and is passed down through generations. it affects the connective tissue in the body, which can lead to issues with the cardiovascular system, skin, and joints.

Ehlers Danlos Syndrome (EDS) is a group of genetic disorders that affect the body's connective tissues, which provide structure and support to various organs and tissues. EDS can cause hypermobility, skin that is hyperextensible and prone to injury, as well as other joint problems. There are different types of EDS, including Hype

Autosomal recessive Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome (Type IV) is a type of Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome characterized by unexpected organ fragility, inconstant physical features such as thin, translucent skin and easy bruising, and acrogeric traits. It has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The exact synonym for this type of Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome is Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome, recessive type 4.

Greig cephalopolysyndactyly syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the presence of an abnormal number of fingers and toes, as well as a distinctive skull shape. The condition is caused by mutations in the GLI3 gene on the short arm of chromosome 2. People with this condition may have limb and facial abnormalities, as well as other health problems such as hearing loss, vision issues, and intellectual disability. It is important for individuals with Greig cephalopolysyndactyly syndrome to be monitored closely by a team of medical professionals who can provide specialized care and support.

Calcaneonavicular coalition is a type of synostosis that occurs when the tarsal and carpal bones fuse together, leading to stiffness in the hands and feet. It is also known as multiple synostosis syndrome or synostoses, tarsal, carpal, and digital.
Larsen syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disorder characterized by large-joint dislocations and distinctive craniofacial abnormalities. It is also known as Dominant Larsen Syndrome.

Renal agenesis is a type of kidney disease that occurs when one or both kidneys fail to develop properly. It can be inherited or caused by environmental factors, and it can lead to various complications if left untreated. The exact synonyms for renal agenesis include hereditary renal aplasia, hereditary urogenital adysplasia, renal adysplasia, and renal aplasia.

Saethre-Chotzen syndrome is a type of acrocephalosyndactylia, which is a congenital disorder characterized by the premature fusion of certain bones in the skull. It is considered to be an autosomal dominant disease, meaning that it can be passed down through family genes. The syndrome is named after two Swiss physicians who first described it in 1950.
It has a material basis in a genetic mutation in the TWIST1 gene which results in premature fusion of skull bones. It also has related synonym acrocephalosyndactyly type III.
Cartilage hair hypoplasia is a type of autosomal recessive disease.

Brittle cornea syndrome 1 is a rare genetic disorder that affects the corneas of individuals, leading to vulnerability and susceptibility to injury. It is classified as an autosomal recessive disease, which means that it is passed down through families by inheritance from both parents, but each parent has only one copy of the faulty gene. The syndrome is characterized by a range of symptoms including blue sclerae (the white part of the eye), corneal rupture after minor trauma, keratoconus or keratoglobus, hyperelasticity of the skin and joints, and increased joint mobility. It has also been linked to mutations in the ZNF469 gene on chromosome 16q24.<|end

Benign Familial Neonatal Epilepsy (BFNE) is a type of epilepsy that affects infants in the first few months of life. It is considered to be a benign, or non-dangerous, condition and usually resolves on its own by the age of 2. BFNE is often inherited through families and can be associated with certain genetic mutations. The seizures associated with BFNE are usually brief and do not cause any long-term problems. Some common triggers for these seizures include fevers, infections, and lack of sleep.

Blepharophimosis, ptosis, epicanthus inversus syndrome is a genetic condition characterized by several distinct physical traits. These may include drooping eyelids (ptosis), an upward slant to the eyelids (epicanthus inversus), and a tendency for the eyelashes to point outwards (telecanthus). The syndrome is also sometimes associated with premature ovarian failure in women. It is caused by mutations in the FOXL2 gene, which is located on chromosome 3q22.3.

Kyphosis has definition A spinal condition characterized by an excessive forward curvature of the upper back, typically in the thoracic spine, resulting from abnormal development or weakening of the spinal ligaments and vertebrae.

Olivopontocerebellar atrophy, also known as Dejerine-Thomas syndrome or Thomas' syndrome, is a type of neurodegenerative disease that affects the cerebellum and pons. It is characterized by progressive cerebellar ataxia, leading to clumsiness in body movements, veering from midline when walking, wide-based stance, and falls without signs of paralysis or weakness. The condition has a material basis in the expansion of CAG triplet repeats (glutamine) which results in degeneration of neurons in the cerebellum, pons, and inferior olives. It is also known as WADIA-SWAMI SYNDROME.

Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia congenita (SEDC) is a type of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia that is characterized by disproportionate short stature, abnormal epiphyses, and flattened vertebral bodies. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the COL2A1 gene on chromosome 12q13.11. SEDC is also known as late-onset spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia because it typically begins to cause symptoms after the age of three.

Leber congenital amaurosis (LCA) is a type of retinal disease that affects the retina and can lead to severe vision loss or blindness. It is characterized by nystagmus, sluggish or no pupillary responses, and vision loss. LCA has its basis in abnormalities in prenatal development or birth, and it is considered a form of congenital stationary night blindness. The exact synonyms for LCA include Leber's amaurosis, Leber's congenital amaurosis, and Leber's disease.
Hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasia is a type of ectodermal dysplasia characterized by the malformation of ectodermal structures including hypotrichosis, hypohidrosis, and hypodontia.

Dubowitz Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects both boys and girls. It is characterized by microcephaly, growth retardation, and a unique facial appearance which includes a narrow or triangular shaped head, micrognathia, ptosis, a broad, wide-tipped nose, and wide-set eyes with drooping eyelids. This condition is caused by an autosomal recessive inheritance and it has a strong genetic component. There is no cure for Dubowitz Syndrome, but early intervention can help improve some of the symptoms.

Blount's disease, also known as familial infantile type osteochondrosis deformans tibiae, is a type of osteochondrodysplasia that results in an inward turning of the lower leg, specifically in the tibia. It is a condition where the bone fails to develop normally, leading to abnormal growth and development. The symptoms typically appear in children between the ages of 2 and 4 years old, and it is more common in boys than girls. Treatment may include surgery or physical therapy, depending on the severity of the condition.

Gingival disease is a specific type of periodontal disease that affects the gums. It can cause inflammation, redness, and swelling around the gingiva (the pink tissue that surrounds the teeth). Gum disease can also lead to tooth loss if left untreated.

Cystic Fibrosis is a genetic disorder that affects the respiratory and digestive systems. It is caused by mutations in the cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator (CFTR) gene, which encodes a chloride channel that is responsible for transporting salt and water into and out of the body's cells. The buildup of thick, sticky mucus in the lungs can lead to chronic infections, while problems with digestion may cause malabsorption of nutrients. Cystic Fibrosis is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the faulty gene (one from each parent) to develop the disease. There is no cure for Cystic Fibrosis, but treatments can help manage symptoms and improve quality of life.

Cystic echinococcosis is a type of bone disease that involves the larvae of Echinococcus granulosus, which can cause abdominal pain, a mass in the hepatic area, and biliary duct obstruction. It can also lead to pulmonary involvement with chest pain, cough, and hemoptysis. Rupture of the cysts produce fever, urticaria, eosinophilia, and anaphylactic shock, as well as cyst dissemination. The disease can affect other organs such as the brain, bone, heart, and infectious diseases like lung, thyroid, liver and unilocular hydatid disease.

Echinococcosis is a type of parasitic infection caused by the larval stages of tapeworms of the genus Echinococcus. It can affect both humans and domestic animals, and can involve infections in various organs such as the liver, lungs, spleen, brain, heart, and kidneys. The disease has exact synonyms such as echinococcal disease, hydatid disease, liver echinoccus, and pulmonary echinococcosis.

Cholera is a type of primary bacterial infectious disease that is characterized by profuse watery diarrhea, vomiting, leg cramps, circulatory collapse and shock. It's caused by infection of the intestine with the bacterium Vibrio cholerae.

Reproductive system disease refers to any condition or illness that affects the reproductive organs in the body. This can include issues with the ovaries, uterus, fallopian tubes, cervix, and other related structures. These diseases can impact a person's ability to conceive, carry a pregnancy to term, or have healthy offspring. Some examples of reproductive system diseases include pelvic inflammatory disease (PID), endometriosis, polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), and infertility.

Yes, that is correct. Mental health diseases are a group of conditions that affect the mind and can have a significant impact on an individual's overall well-being. Some common examples include depression, anxiety, bipolar disorder, schizophrenia, and personality disorders. These conditions can cause distress, disrupt daily life, and impair an individual's ability to function in social or work-related situations.

Candidiasis is a type of fungal infection caused by the overgrowth of Candida yeasts in the body. It most commonly affects the mouth, throat, skin, scalp, and vagina, but it can also occur in other areas of the body such as the bronchi, lungs, heart, and brain. Candidiasis is often seen in individuals who have weakened immune systems, such as those with HIV/AIDS or cancer undergoing chemotherapy. It can be treated with antifungal medications.

avoidant personality disorder is a mental health condition in which a person has an intense fear of social rejection and criticism. They may avoid social interactions altogether or feel extremely uncomfortable in social situations. People with this disorder often have low self-esteem, feelings of inadequacy, and are highly sensitive to the opinions of others. It is important to seek professional help if you or someone you know may be struggling with avoidant personality disorder.

Personality disorder is a mental health condition characterized by long-term patterns of thoughts, behaviors, and emotional responses that are abnormal or distressing to the individual. These patterns can cause significant difficulties in social interactions and relationships, as well as in one's work or school life.
It is important to note that personality disorders are not personality traits or flaws, but rather a result of complex brain chemistry and environmental factors. Additionally, it is essential to seek professional help for the diagnosis and treatment of personality disorder.

Chronic gonorrhea of the cervix, also known as chronic cervicitis, is a condition characterized by persistent inflammation or infection of the cervix (the entrance to the uterus) caused by the bacterium Neisseria gonorrhoeae. It can cause pain, discharge, and other symptoms, and if left untreated can lead to complications such as infertility and increased risk of pelvic inflammatory disease (PID). Treatment typically involves antibiotics, and it is important to follow up with a healthcare provider to ensure the infection has been fully treated.

Chronic cervicitis is a specific type of cervicitis characterized by persistent inflammation in the cervical area for an extended period, typically ranging from several weeks to months or even years. This condition can lead to complications if left untreated and may require medical intervention to manage symptoms effectively.

Symptoms of chronic cervicitis include vaginal discharge with a foul odor, abnormal bleeding between periods, lower back pain, and pelvic pain. These symptoms can vary in severity among individuals and may worsen over time if the condition remains untreated. It is essential to consult a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment of chronic cervicitis to avoid complications and ensure overall reproductive health.

Cecal benign neoplasm, also known as a cecum neoplasm or neoplasm of the caecum, is a type of benign intestinal tumor that originates in the cecum, which is the first portion of the large intestine. It is characterized by an abnormal growth of cells in the cecum, resulting in a mass or lump that can cause symptoms such as abdominal pain, constipation, and blood in the stool.
While it is not cancerous, cecal benign neoplasm can still be a significant source of discomfort and may require surgical intervention to remove the affected portion of the intestine. It is important for individuals who experience symptoms related to cecal benign neoplasm to seek medical attention from a qualified healthcare provider to properly diagnose and treat the condition.

Cecal disease, also known as cecal volvulus or intestinal obstruction, is a condition where the cecum, a pouch-like structure in the lower part of the small intestine, twists and becomes blocked. This can cause severe pain, vomiting, and other symptoms, and if not treated promptly, it can lead to life-threatening complications such as bowel obstruction or perforation. It is important to seek medical attention immediately if you suspect you have cecal disease. Treatment typically involves surgery to remove the affected portion of the intestine and restore normal function. Prevention strategies may include maintaining a healthy diet, staying hydrated, and avoiding excessive straining during bowel movements.

Cecum carcinoma is a type of cancer that originates in the cecum, which is part of the large intestine. It is characterized by abnormal cell growth and division, leading to the formation of a tumor. This condition can be caused by various factors, such as exposure to harmful substances, chronic inflammation, or inherited genetic mutations.
Cecum carcinoma can be difficult to diagnose because it shares many similarities with other types of cancer that affect the large intestine. However, a biopsy and imaging tests such as CT scans or MRI can help identify the presence of tumors in the cecum.
Treatment options for cecum carcinoma may include surgery to remove the tumor and surrounding tissue, chemotherapy to kill cancer cells, and radiation therapy to destroy cancer cells. The choice of treatment depends on factors such as the size and location of the tumor, as well as the patient's overall health and preferences.
It is important for individuals to maintain a healthy lifestyle, including regular exercise and a balanced diet, to reduce their risk of developing cancer. Additionally, it is recommended that those at high risk for certain types of cancer undergo periodic screenings to detect the disease early.

colon carcinoma is a type of cancer that affects the colon. It occurs when there is an abnormal growth of cells in the colon, which can eventually lead to the development of a tumor. The disease has its location on the colon and is characterized by abnormal cell proliferation. It's also referred to as carcinoma of the colon or colon cancer.

Cecum cancer, also known as cecal cancer, is a type of large intestine cancer that occurs in the cecum. It refers to the growth of abnormal cells in this part of the body, which can lead to the formation of a tumor or malignant neoplasm. The term "cecum" refers to the initial portion of the large intestine, where food is stored before being passed into the colon.

Cecum cancer can be a challenging diagnosis due to its location and rarity compared to other types of colorectal cancer. It is essential for patients to receive proper treatment and care from experienced medical professionals who have knowledge about this specific type of cancer.

Treatment options may include surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, or a combination of these approaches. The choice of treatment will depend on various factors such as the stage of the cancer, overall health, and personal preferences. It is crucial to discuss all available treatment options with your doctor to make an informed decision about the best course of action for your specific case of cecum cancer.

In summary, cecum cancer refers to a type of large intestine cancer that occurs in the cecum and involves abnormal cell growth. It is essential to receive proper treatment and care from experienced medical professionals who are knowledgeable about this specific type of cancer. Treatment options may include surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, or a combination of these approaches, depending on various factors such as the stage of the cancer, overall health, and personal preferences.

Cecum Lymphoma is a rare and aggressive type of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma that affects the cecum, a pouch-like structure in the large intestine. It is also known as cecal lymphoid hyperplasia or enteric-type extra-nodal marginal zone B-cell lymphoma of mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue (MALT). The exact cause of Cecum Lymphoma is not yet fully understood, but it is believed to be related to abnormalities in the immune system and exposure to certain environmental factors.

Colon Lymphoma, also known as Colonic Lymphoma, is a type of cancer that affects the lymphatic system in the colon. It is a malignant growth of lymphoid tissue and can spread to other parts of the body if left untreated. Symptoms include abdominal pain, bloating, diarrhea, constipation, weight loss, and blood in the stool. Treatment options may vary depending on the stage and location of the cancer, but may include surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, or a combination of these treatments. Early detection through regular screening tests such as colonoscopy can improve outcomes.

Nodular nonsuppurative panniculitis is a specific type of panniculitis characterized by the inflammation and thickening of subcutaneous tissue. It has several synonyms, including relapsing febrile nodular nonsuppurative panniculitis, Weber-Christian disease, and nodular non-suppurative feverish panniculitis. These terms are used interchangeably to describe the same condition.

That is correct! Panniculitis is a type of skin disease that affects the subcutaneous adipose tissue, characterized by inflammation and swelling. It can be caused by various factors such as infections, autoimmune disorders, or trauma. Treatment usually involves antibiotics, anti-inflammatory medications, and rest to allow the affected area to heal properly.

Penile disease refers to a medical condition that affects the penis, which is a part of the male reproductive system. It can occur due to various factors such as infection, inflammation, or trauma. Some common types of penile diseases include epididymitis, orchitis, balanitis, and urethritis. These conditions can cause symptoms like pain, swelling, itching, or discharge, and may require treatment from a healthcare provider to manage the symptoms and prevent further complications.

Pleural disease refers to a variety of conditions that affect the pleura, which is the membrane that surrounds the lungs and lines the chest cavity. These diseases may involve inflammation of the pleura, accumulation of air or fluid in the pleural space, abnormal growths on the pleura (such as pleural tumors), or thickening of the pleura (pleural plaques). Some common causes of pleural disease include congestive heart failure, malignancy, parapneumonic infections, and pulmonary embolism. The main symptom of pleural disease is chest pain, which can be accompanied by other symptoms such as coughing up blood, shortness of breath, and fever. Treatment for pleural disease depends on the underlying cause and may involve medications, surgery, or a combination of both.

Mixed cell type cancer is a term used to describe a cancer that has elements of both epithelial and mesenchymal cells. It is also known as malignant mixed tumor or malignant mixed neoplasm. This type of cancer can develop from abnormal proliferation of cells that have a material basis in two germinal layers of tissue, such as the ectoderm and endoderm, or the ectoderm and mesoderm. It is important to note that the term "cancer" here refers specifically to malignant cancer, which is characterized by the uncontrolled growth of abnormal cells in the body.

Parathyroid carcinoma is a rare type of cancer that originates in the parathyroid gland, which is located in the neck. It is considered an endocrine gland cancer because it affects hormone production. The exact synonyms for this condition include carcinoma of Parathyroid gland, malignant neoplasm of parathyroid gland, and malignant tumor of parathyroid gland. It can also be referred to as a parathyroid gland neoplasm or a neoplasm of the parathyroid gland. Parathyroid carcinoma is different from Parathyroid adenocarcinoma, which is another type of cancer that originates in the parathyroid gland but is considered to be a different subtype of endocrine gland cancer.

head and neck carcinoma is a type of head and neck cancer.
head and neck carcinoma is a type of malignancy that affects the upper aerodigestive tract, including the lip, oral cavity (mouth), nasal cavity, paranasal sinuses, pharynx, and larynx.

head and neck carcinoma has related synonyms including malignant neoplasm of the upper aerodigestive tract, epithelial cell-derived cancer of the head and neck, and squamous cell carcinoma of the neck..

Vibratory urticaria is a type of physical urticaria that is characterized by itching, reddish skin, and swelling within minutes of local exposure to dermal vibration. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the ADGRE2 gene on chromosome 19p13.

That is correct. Urticaria, also known as hives, is a skin condition characterized by the appearance of raised, red, itchy bumps on the skin. These bumps are caused by an inflammatory response in the upper dermis layer of the skin. The exact cause of urticaria can vary, but common triggers include allergies, medications, and physical factors such as pressure or temperature changes.

Arthus reaction is a type of hypersensitivity reaction, also known as Type III disease. It is characterized by local vasculitis, which can cause symptoms such as pain, edema, hemorrhage or necrosis. The condition is thought to be caused by the deposition of antigen-antibody immune complexes in vascular or serosal walls.
Arthus reaction is also known as Arthus phenomenon and Arthus type urticaria.

Hypersensitivity reaction type III disease, also known as immune complex disease, is a type of hypersensitivity reaction characterized by the accumulation of antigen-antibody immune complexes in the body. This can lead to an inflammatory response and damage to the affected tissues. It is important for individuals with this condition to receive proper medical treatment and care to manage their symptoms and prevent further complications.

Angioedema is a type of skin disease that is characterized by one or more areas of well-demarcated, non-pitting edema of deep subcutaneous tissues. It is also known as Quincke's edema or angioneurotic edema.

Cognitive disorders are a group of mental health conditions that affect cognitive functions such as memory, perception, and problem-solving. They can also impact an individual's ability to learn, adapt, and perform daily activities. There are many different types of cognitive disorders, including attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD), dementia, stroke, and traumatic brain injury.

Cognitive disorders can have a significant impact on an individual's quality of life, as they often lead to difficulties in communication, social interactions, and independent living. Early detection and intervention are crucial for managing the symptoms and improving outcomes for those with cognitive disorders. Treatment options may include medications, therapy, and lifestyle changes, depending on the specific type of cognitive disorder and its underlying cause. It is important to consult with a healthcare professional if you or someone you know is experiencing symptoms of cognitive disorders.

Chromoblastomycosis is a type of subcutaneous mycosis, which is a chronic subcutaneous fungal infection that presents as nodular or verrucoid, ulcerated, or crusted skin lesions on exposed areas of skin. It is caused by Fonsecaea pedrosoi, Fonsecaea compacta, Cladophialophora carrionii or Phialophora verrucosa. Histological examination reveals muriform cells (with perpendicular septations) or thick walled, dark-colored, rounded forms (copper pennies) that are characteristic of this infection. The exact synonyms for Chromoblastomycosis are Chromomycosis and Mossy foot disease.
Dermatomycosis is a type of cutaneous mycosis that results in a fungal infection located in the skin or its appendages, and has a material basis in Ascomycota fungi other than dermatophytes.

You are correct. Fungal infectious disease refers to a disease caused by an infectious agent that has a material basis in fungi and can infect humans or animals, often causing infections by passing through resistance barriers of the host body. Another term for this type of disease is mycosis. Additionally, related synonyms include mycoses.

Ectropion is a medical condition that affects the eyelid, causing it to turn outward or away from the eye. It can occur due to various factors such as aging, trauma, infection, or surgery. Ectropion can cause discomfort and may lead to problems with vision if left untreated. Treatment options include eyelid surgery, medications, or skin grafts. It's important to consult a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment of this condition.

Normal pressure hydrocephalus (NPH) is a type of communicating hydrocephalus that results from a blockage in the normal flow of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) through the ventricular system. It is also known as low-pressure hydrocephalus, as it is characterized by low pressure within the brain's ventricles.

Symptoms of NPH may include gait disturbances, urinary incontinence, and cognitive impairment. These symptoms can be caused by a buildup of CSF within the brain and spinal cord, which puts pressure on these structures. Treatment for NPH typically involves surgical intervention to create a pathway for the CSF to flow properly through the ventricular system.

It is important to note that there are different types of hydrocephalus, and not all cases of hydrocephalus will present with the same symptoms or require the same treatment. It is always advisable to consult with a medical professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.
